                    "description": "Very long-lived asymptotic limit: τ_A = 1e6·yr·s = 31557600000000.0 s (~1 million years, beyond any real GHG), a_A = 1.0, t_f = 100·yr·s. Result: GWP = 1.3700303905452804 (~37% above CO₂'s impact — the asymptotic limit a_A · t_f / decay_integral_CO2). decay_integral_A = 3155602217.259511 s (≈ t_f since 100·yr << 1e6·yr means the species has barely decayed) while decay_integral_CO2 = 2303308188.662561 s (49% of τ_CO2). Reproduces the upstream `GWP_exponential function` test (GasChem.jl test/climate_forcing_test.jl:223-237) very-long-lived case which asserts GWP_exponential(1e6, 1, 100) ≈ 100/(150·(1-exp(-100/150))) = 100/72.987... = 1.3700... at rtol=0.01 (within 1% of the asymptotic τ_A → ∞ limit a_A · t_f / [τ_CO2 · (1 - exp(-t_f/τ_CO2))]). The .esm migration tightens the assertion to rel=1e-10 on the closed-form value 1.37003... — the 0.001% deviation from the exact asymptotic limit 100/72.987 = 1.37005... reflects the exp(-100/1e6) ≈ 1 - 1e-4 first-order Taylor correction term that keeps decay_integral_A slightly below t_f.",
