                            "description": "CH₄ GWP as a function of time horizon t_f on a log-log plot, swept from 5·yr (short policy emphasis) to 1000·yr (multi-millennium horizon) at τ_A = 12·yr fixed. Strictly decreasing curve passing through the canonical IPCC values: GWP₂₀ ≈ 72 at t_f = 20·yr, GWP₁₀₀ ≈ 23 at t_f = 100·yr, GWP₅₀₀ ≈ 7 at t_f = 500·yr. The shape illustrates the short-lived-species GWP-vs-t_f decay: as t_f grows, the species' contribution saturates at τ_A while CO₂'s keeps growing, so the ratio decreases monotonically.",
                            "x": {"variable": "t_f", "label": "t_f (s)"},
                            "y": {"variable": "GWP", "label": "GWP (dimensionless)"}
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "species_lifetime_sweep_at_gwp100",
                    "description": "Sweep species lifetime τ_A across 6 orders of magnitude [1·day, 100000·yr] at the GWP₁₀₀ reporting horizon (t_f = 100·yr fixed) and a_A = 100 fixed. Surfaces the canonical GWP-vs-τ_A monotonicity from S&P Figure 23.15 (alternate cut): GWP rises sharply from near-zero at τ_A → 0 (species disappears too fast to contribute), transitions through ~a_A · τ_A / decay_integral_CO2 (saturated species contributes a fixed amount), and asymptotes to ~a_A · t_f / decay_integral_CO2 in the τ_A → ∞ limit. The crossover region is around τ_A ~ τ_CO2 = 150 yr where the species and CO₂ have similar integration behaviors. Anchors the design observation that very-short-lived species have low GWP regardless of their radiative efficiency, while very-long-lived species saturate at the asymptotic a_A · t_f / decay_integral_CO2 limit independent of τ_A.",
